diff:1194122357:1194007547:=25,26c25,27%0a%3c I shall simply reprint these rules from his book  ''A Guidebook for the Beginning Sweeper''.   Mr. Whidden has  lovingly given his rules a name,%0a%3c and that is:  ``The Moscow Rules". I don't  know what it specifically%0a---%0a> I shall simply reprint these rules from his book  ``A GUIDEBOOK FOR THE%0a> BEGINNING SWEEPER".   Mr. Whidden has  lovingly given his rules a name,%0a> and that is:  ``THE MOSCOW RULES".    I  dont  know what it specifically%0a33,44c34,45%0a%3c # Assume that all Local Nationals's (LN)are hostile.%0a%3c # Assume that an approach by a non-LN is hostile until proven otherwise.%0a%3c # Assume that there is always hostile physical surveillance unless counter-surveillance proves otherwise.%0a%3c # Assume that all telephone conversations are monitored by LN's.%0a%3c # Assume that all enclosed areas are bugged unless they are 'secure' rooms.%0a%3c # Assume that incoming and outgoing mail will be subject to hostile examination.%0a%3c # Assume that anything that is left unattended will be subject to examination by LN's.%0a%3c # Assume that locks left unguarded or unprotected will be manipulated or bypased and the material they protect will be compromised.%0a%3c # Assume that simple traps will not deceive LN's.%0a%3c # Assume that any guard can be recruited by LN's or is himself an LN agent.%0a%3c # Assume that a pair of guards can be recruited by LN's or are themselves agents of LN's.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> * Assume that all LN's are hostile.%0a> * Assume that an approach by a non-LN is hostile until proven otherwise.%0a> * Assume that there is always hostile physical surveillance unless counter-surveillance proves otherwise.%0a> * Assume that all telephone conversations are monitored by LN's.%0a> * Assume that all enclosed areas are bugged unless they are 'secure' rooms.%0a> * Assume that incoming and outgoing mail will be subject to hostile examination.%0a> * Assume that anything that is left unattended will be subject to examination by LN's.%0a> * Assume that locks left unguarded or unprotected will be manipulated or bypased and the material they protect will be compromised.%0a> * Assume that simple traps will not deceive LN's.%0a> * Assume that any guard can be recruited by LN's or is himself an LN agent.%0a> * Assume that a pair of guards can be recruited by LN's or are themselves agents of LN's.%0a> %0a48,54c49,55%0a%3c # Assume that the eavesdropper is listening in the sensitve areas.%0a%3c # Assume that an eavesdropper has an agent near the sensitive area.%0a%3c # Assume that the eavesdropper is watching the entrances of the facility.%0a%3c # Assume that the eavesdropper can maintain a low vulnerability status when he is not listening.%0a%3c # Assume that the eavesdropper is guarding the NLJD band of frequencies.%0a%3c # Assume that the eavesdropper is watching for sweep receiver radiation.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> * Assume that the eavesdropper is listening in the sensitve areas.%0a> * Assume that an eavesdropper has an agent near the sensitive area.%0a> * Assume that the eavesdropper is watching the entrances of the facility.%0a> * Assume that the eavesdropper can maintain a low vulnerability status when he is not listening.%0a> * Assume that the eavesdropper is guarding the NLJD band of frequencies.%0a> * Assume that the eavesdropper is watching for sweep receiver radiation.%0a> %0a64,86c65,83%0a%3c Local Nationals%0a%3c ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%3c %0a%3c The term  LN (Local National) means a person who is indigenous to a%0a%3c specific area.  This term has a greater meaning in the field of world%0a%3c intelligence as it means a citizen of a foreign country who may be an%0a%3c agent or informer of that country or it may be a citizen of another%0a%3c country that you recruit as an ``agent" or "asset" to work for you.%0a%3c %0a%3c However, in the context of the Moscow Rules it is simply a term of%0a%3c convenience which is not nearly so grand. In such context of the rules%0a%3c it refers to a person who may work for an organization or a corporation%0a%3c who is either acting on its own accord or under the direction of others%0a%3c and the purpose of that individual is to infiltrate and or compromise%0a%3c the corporation or organization usually in a covert manner (such as to%0a%3c steal business secrets in industrial espionage), but can be done in an%0a%3c overt manner also if the intent is to destroy or cause harm or embarress%0a%3c the organization.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Moscow Rules for Counter Espionage Investigations%0a%3c =================================================%0a%3c %0a---%0a> First, Mr. Whidden uses the term  ``LN" (which stands for Local National)%0a> which means a person who is indigenous to a specific area.  This term has%0a> a greater meaning in the field of world intelligence as it means a citizen%0a> of a foreign country who may be an agent or informer of that country or it%0a> may be a citizen of another country that you recruit as an ``agent" or%0a> "asset" to work for you.  However, in the context of the Moscow Rules it%0a> is simply a term of convenience which is not nearly so grande. In such%0a> context of the rules it merely refers to a person who may work for an%0a> organization or a corporation who is either acting on their own accord or%0a> under the direction of others and the purpose of that individual is to%0a> infiltrate and or compromise the corporation or organization usually in a%0a> covert manner (such as to steal business secrets in industrial espionage),%0a> but can be done in an overt manner also if the intent is to destroy or cause%0a> harm or embarress the organization.%0a> %0a> %0a> MOSCOW RULES FOR COUNTER ESPIONAGE INVESTIGATIONS:%0a> ==================================================%0a> %0a90,119c87,112%0a%3c Rule 1 ``Assume all Local Nationals are hostile" translates to the%0a%3c philosophy of ``trust nobody!" %0a%3c This can be extended to include the very person who hired you.  %0a%3c This is a logical conclusion when you strictly construe these rules;%0a%3c especially in a corporate situation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c One interesting tactic has the security detail request that a TSCM%0a%3c countermeasures sweep be performed. They may request the sweep to%0a%3c satisfy a boss or to make the executives feel that the room is more%0a%3c secure after the sweep so they will have a confidential converation.%0a%3c %0a%3c However, one or more of the security detail may be the actual%0a%3c perpetrator and either deactivate or remove the clandestine devices%0a%3c before the search, and reactivate or replace the device afterwards.%0a%3c %0a%3c What makes this tactic more powerful is the target will trust the agent%0a%3c for ordering the sweep. This also makes the agent's cover appear more%0a%3c legitimate becuase he ordered the sweep.%0a%3c %0a%3c One can reference Moscow Rules 10 & 11 to realize that ``guards" and%0a%3c ``security" should not never be given full trust.  %0a%3c %0a%3c The ``Sweeper" ''must'' obey the security staff, even if the sweeper%0a%3c suspects the guards or security staff as being the actual perpetrators.%0a%3c %0a%3c Once actual proof is established to concurr that a staffer or guard is%0a%3c an agent, the sweeper should convey that possibility to some other%0a%3c person within the company who the sweeper feels is trustworthy.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> Rule 1 which states that you should assume that all LN's are hostile%0a> roughly translates to the philosophy of   ``trust nobody!" This is%0a> extended to include the very person who hired you!  As unlikely as it%0a> may seem, if you look at the rules it is a very logical conclusion,%0a> especially in a corporate situation.  It is very common for the%0a> ``security department"  to be the one to request that a TSCM%0a> countermeasures sweep be performed, this can be done to please the%0a> bosses and make the executives feel that since the sweep was done all%0a> the confidential conversations are secure.  In a real world situation it%0a> is likely that one or more individuals in the 'security department'%0a> itself may be the actual perpetrator and they thusly will be well aware%0a> of the search for eavesdropping devices and they will have the ability%0a> to easily deactivate or remove the clandestine devices before the%0a> search, wheras they can be replaced promptly after the search was%0a> performed. This tactic of infiltration not only gives the eavesdroppers%0a> the advatage of knowing when a sweep is to be performed but also%0a> provides a form of 'cover' since the security employee (really an LN%0a> ``agent") will seem all the more legitimate since he is the one that%0a> ordered the sweep.  One can reference Moscow Rules 10 & 11 to realize%0a> that ``guards" and ``security" should not usually be given 100 percent%0a> trust.  The ``SWEEPER"  MUST obey what the security staff says, even if%0a> the sweeper suspects the guards or security staff as being the actual%0a> perpetrators, and once actual proof is established to concurr that fact,%0a> the sweeper should convey that possibility to some other person within%0a> the company who the sweeper feels is trustworthy.%0a> %0a123,128c116,120%0a%3c Rule 4 is an especially important one. ``Assume all telephone%0a%3c conversations are monitored." Although it needs no elaboration, I cannot%0a%3c stress how important it is '''never''' to discuss anything sensitive%0a%3c over a telephone. This holds espeicially true when you have a cordless%0a%3c or cellular phone.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> Rule 4 is an especially important one. Although it needs no elaboration,%0a> I cannot stress how important it is NEVER EVER to discuss anything%0a> sensitive over a telephone (that is even more so true if you have a%0a> cordles or cellular phone).%0a> %0a130c122%0a%3c encrypted phones/faxes should be beyond suspicion. There exists many%0a---%0a> encrypted phones/faxes should be beyond suspicion. Their exists many%0a139c131%0a%3c help secure the units key integrity, but there are ways around that.%0a---%0a> help secure the units key integrity, but their are ways around that.%0a157c149%0a%3c A ``secure" room is a complicated term to define as there are many%0a---%0a> A ``secure" room is a complicated term to define as their are many%0a167c159%0a%3c the room would be acoustically secure which means there would be%0a---%0a> the room would be acoustically secure which means their would be%0a172c164%0a%3c and continuously fed into the secure room. There should be several of%0a---%0a> and continuously fed into the secure room. Their should be several of%0a336d327%0a%3c %0a
