diff:1194007547:1194006982:=34,45c34,51%0a%3c * Assume that all LN's are hostile.%0a%3c * Assume that an approach by a non-LN is hostile until proven otherwise.%0a%3c * Assume that there is always hostile physical surveillance unless counter-surveillance proves otherwise.%0a%3c * Assume that all telephone conversations are monitored by LN's.%0a%3c * Assume that all enclosed areas are bugged unless they are 'secure' rooms.%0a%3c * Assume that incoming and outgoing mail will be subject to hostile examination.%0a%3c * Assume that anything that is left unattended will be subject to examination by LN's.%0a%3c * Assume that locks left unguarded or unprotected will be manipulated or bypased and the material they protect will be compromised.%0a%3c * Assume that simple traps will not deceive LN's.%0a%3c * Assume that any guard can be recruited by LN's or is himself an LN agent.%0a%3c * Assume that a pair of guards can be recruited by LN's or are themselves agents of LN's.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> (1) Assume that all LN's are hostile.%0a> (2) Assume that an approach by a non-LN is hostile until proven otherwise.%0a> (3) Assume that there is always hostile physical surveillance unless%0a>     counter-surveillance proves otherwise.%0a> (4) Assume that all telephone conversations are monitored by LN's.%0a> (5) Assume that all enclosed areas are bugged unless they are 'secure' rooms.%0a> (6) Assume that incoming and outgoing mail will be subject to hostile%0a>     examination.%0a> (7) Assume that anything that is left unattended will be subject to%0a>     examination by LN's.%0a> (8) Assume that locks left unguarded or unprotected will be manipulated%0a>     or bypased and the material they protect will be compromised.%0a> (9) Assume that simple traps will not deceive LN's.%0a> (10) Assume that any guard can be recruited by LN's or is himself%0a>     an LN agent.%0a> (11) Assume that a pair of guards can be recruited by LN's or are%0a>     themselves agents of LN's.%0a> %0a49,55c55,62%0a%3c * Assume that the eavesdropper is listening in the sensitve areas.%0a%3c * Assume that an eavesdropper has an agent near the sensitive area.%0a%3c * Assume that the eavesdropper is watching the entrances of the facility.%0a%3c * Assume that the eavesdropper can maintain a low vulnerability status when he is not listening.%0a%3c * Assume that the eavesdropper is guarding the NLJD band of frequencies.%0a%3c * Assume that the eavesdropper is watching for sweep receiver radiation.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> (1) Assume that the eavesdropper is listening in the sensitve areas.%0a> (2) Assume that an eavesdropper has an agent near the sensitive area.%0a> (3) Assume that the eavesdropper is watching the entrances of the facility.%0a> (4) Assume that the eavesdropper can maintain a low vulnerability status%0a>     when he is not listening.%0a> (5) Assume that the eavesdropper is guarding the NLJD band of frequencies.%0a> (6) Assume that the eavesdropper is watching for sweep receiver radiation.%0a> %0a82,203c89,198%0a%3c ==================================================%0a%3c %0a%3c Rule One%0a%3c ~~~~~~~~%0a%3c %0a%3c Rule 1 which states that you should assume that all LN's are hostile%0a%3c roughly translates to the philosophy of   ``trust nobody!" This is%0a%3c extended to include the very person who hired you!  As unlikely as it%0a%3c may seem, if you look at the rules it is a very logical conclusion,%0a%3c especially in a corporate situation.  It is very common for the%0a%3c ``security department"  to be the one to request that a TSCM%0a%3c countermeasures sweep be performed, this can be done to please the%0a%3c bosses and make the executives feel that since the sweep was done all%0a%3c the confidential conversations are secure.  In a real world situation it%0a%3c is likely that one or more individuals in the 'security department'%0a%3c itself may be the actual perpetrator and they thusly will be well aware%0a%3c of the search for eavesdropping devices and they will have the ability%0a%3c to easily deactivate or remove the clandestine devices before the%0a%3c search, wheras they can be replaced promptly after the search was%0a%3c performed. This tactic of infiltration not only gives the eavesdroppers%0a%3c the advatage of knowing when a sweep is to be performed but also%0a%3c provides a form of 'cover' since the security employee (really an LN%0a%3c ``agent") will seem all the more legitimate since he is the one that%0a%3c ordered the sweep.  One can reference Moscow Rules 10 & 11 to realize%0a%3c that ``guards" and ``security" should not usually be given 100 percent%0a%3c trust.  The ``SWEEPER"  MUST obey what the security staff says, even if%0a%3c the sweeper suspects the guards or security staff as being the actual%0a%3c perpetrators, and once actual proof is established to concurr that fact,%0a%3c the sweeper should convey that possibility to some other person within%0a%3c the company who the sweeper feels is trustworthy.%0a%3c %0a%3c Rule 4%0a%3c ~~~~~~%0a%3c %0a%3c Rule 4 is an especially important one. Although it needs no elaboration,%0a%3c I cannot stress how important it is NEVER EVER to discuss anything%0a%3c sensitive over a telephone (that is even more so true if you have a%0a%3c cordles or cellular phone).%0a%3c %0a%3c Also, it should also be noted in my personal opinion, that not even%0a%3c encrypted phones/faxes should be beyond suspicion. Their exists many%0a%3c ways to defeat such encryption. The easiest is simply to compromise the%0a%3c keys which is not a difficult task if your target is unaware. A simple%0a%3c blag-bag job is all that is needed to either liberate the codes from the%0a%3c encryption unit itself or from a locked safe or drawer which can then be%0a%3c copied to floppy and the original code returned to its position%0a%3c undisturbed.  Modern encryption units such as the STU phones do help to%0a%3c some small extent to guard against such attacks by the uses of%0a%3c ``ignition or code keys" which can be physically taken from the unit to%0a%3c help secure the units key integrity, but their are ways around that.%0a%3c Then of course, it is never beyond reason to doubt that the encryption%0a%3c itself can be cracked if it is deemed a priority. This is a mere simple%0a%3c task which can be done in a half a second if your using weak encryption%0a%3c on your phone such as simple ``inversion" chips or other simple%0a%3c encryption units which are widly sold in catalogs.  It is also not out%0a%3c of reason to realize that even DES is not safe anymore, although its a%0a%3c hell of alot safer than ``inversion chips" which can be cracked with a%0a%3c $50 kit available in the classifieds of most electronic magazines.%0a%3c %0a%3c Rule 5%0a%3c ~~~~~~%0a%3c %0a%3c Rule 5 states that all conversations should be considered vulnerable%0a%3c unless conducted in a ``secure" room.   Personally, I hold to the%0a%3c philosophy that *there is no such thing* as a ``secure" room, but then one%0a%3c must realize that this is reality and you cannot be completely paranoid.%0a%3c %0a%3c A ``secure" room is a complicated term to define as their are many%0a%3c degrees of what is considered ``secure".  The ultimate ``secure" room%0a%3c would be completely RF (Radio Frequency) proof and would thusly%0a%3c attenuate completely all RF transmissions from ``bugs", but the security%0a%3c must be extended to insure that no wires/fiber enter the room or leave%0a%3c the room as they can carry clandestine signals hidden on that wire (or%0a%3c at the very least all wires must be monitored for hidden signals). The%0a%3c room must have no loudspeakers which can act as microphones, the room%0a%3c preferable would have no windows and if it did would attenute any%0a%3c Infrared light so as to protect against RF/IR transmitters. And lastly%0a%3c the room would be acoustically secure which means their would be%0a%3c virtually no acoustic leakage (in otherwords no sound could be heard on%0a%3c the other side of the wall using any types of devices such as%0a%3c microphones and high powered amplifiers.) Also, to be acoustically%0a%3c secure, the room should have sufficient random masking signals present%0a%3c and continuously fed into the secure room. Their should be several of%0a%3c such masking generators in use at different points in the room and in%0a%3c addition all plenums and air vents should be masked as well. In%0a%3c addition, the walls as well as any windows should be masked using a%0a%3c transducer element which vibrates all windows and walls in a random%0a%3c fashion to further defeat any clandestine listening devices such as%0a%3c contact microphones, spike or tube microphones which are drilled into%0a%3c the wall from the opposite non-guarded side, as well as techniques of%0a%3c 'laser/microwave pick-off'.%0a%3c %0a%3c Rule 8%0a%3c ~~~~~~%0a%3c %0a%3c Rule 8 also warrants elaboration. All mechanical locking mechanisms are%0a%3c easily bypassed by persons with experience in such fields - which very%0a%3c often includes an eavesdropper himself - or on occasion, an eavesdropper%0a%3c may have a  ``keyman"  which is a person who is an entry specialist%0a%3c (called ``quick-entry" in the locksmithing field).%0a%3c %0a%3c To properly secure a facility electronic locking mechanisms should be%0a%3c used which are much harder (yet not impossible to defeat).  Preferably a%0a%3c secure installation should go beyond simple electronic locking%0a%3c mechanisms (such as key card system connected to an electric strike). A%0a%3c complete access system must be incorporated with full provisions for%0a%3c software logging of all entries and exits, as well as ``anti-passback"%0a%3c protection to further enhance accountability and security and tracking.%0a%3c %0a%3c All safes should be of the electronic type, NOT the mechanical%0a%3c combination type of yesteryear.  It is not a difficult task to bypass%0a%3c combination safes nowadays.  The top expert safecrackers can ply their%0a%3c trade in an hour to two hours time, and a device now exists on the%0a%3c market which cracks safes automatically using a computer controlled%0a%3c mechanism and does so in approximately 1 hour.  Electronic safes are%0a%3c virtually 100 percent secure and are the current standard on all%0a%3c government facilities where classified information is stored. The%0a%3c electronic safe itself should preferably have accountability and logging%0a%3c features built-in with seperate access codes for multiple users of that%0a%3c safe.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a---%0a> (1) Rule 1 which states that you should assume that all LN's are hostile%0a>     roughly translates to the philosophy of   ``trust nobody!"%0a>     This is extended to include the very person who hired you!%0a>     As unlikely as it may seem, if you look at the rules it is a very%0a>     logical conclusion, especially in a corporate situation.  It is%0a>     very common for the  ``security department"  to be the one to request%0a>     that a TSCM countermeasures sweep be performed, this can be done%0a>     to please the bosses and make the executives feel that since the%0a>     sweep was done all the confidential conversations are secure.%0a>     In a real world situation it is likely that one or more individuals%0a>     in the 'security department' itself may be the actual perpetrator%0a>     and they thusly will be well aware of the search for eavesdropping%0a>     devices and they will have the ability to easily deactivate or remove%0a>     the clandestine devices before the search, wheras they can be replaced%0a>     promptly after the search was performed. This tactic of infiltration%0a>     not only gives the eavesdroppers the advatage of knowing when a sweep%0a>     is to be performed but also provides a form of 'cover' since the security%0a>     employee (really an LN ``agent") will seem all the more legitimate%0a>     since he is the one that ordered the sweep.  One can reference%0a>     Moscow Rules 10 & 11 to rea