g a transducer element which%0a>     vibrates all windows and walls in a random fashion to further defeat%0a>     any clandestine listening devices such as contact microphones, spike%0a>     or tube microphones which are drilled into the wall from the opposite%0a>     non-guarded side, as well as techniques of 'laser/microwave pick-off'.%0a> %0a> (8) Rule 8 also warrants elaboration. All mechanical locking mechanisms%0a>     are easily bypassed by persons with experience in such fields -%0a>     which very often includes an eavesdropper himself - or on occasion,%0a>     an eavesdropper may have a  ``keyman"  which is a person who is%0a>     an entry specialist (called ``quick-entry" in the locksmithing field).%0a> %0a>     To properly secure a facility electronic locking mechanisms should%0a>     be used which are much harder (yet not impossible to defeat).%0a>     Preferably a secure installation should go beyond simple electronic%0a>     locking mechanisms (such as key card system connected to an%0a>     electric strike). A complete access system must be incorporated%0a>     with full provisions for software logging of all entries and%0a>     exits, as well as ``anti-passback" protection to further enhance%0a>     accountability and security and tracking.%0a> %0a>     All safes should be of the electronic type, NOT the mechanical%0a>     combination type of yesteryear.  It is not a difficult task to%0a>     bypass combination safes nowadays.  The top expert safecrackers can%0a>     ply their trade in an hour to two hours time, and a device now exists%0a>     on the market which cracks safes automatically using a computer%0a>     controlled mechanism and does so in approximately 1 hour.%0a>     Electronic safes are virtually 100 percent secure and are the current%0a>     standard on all government facilities where classified information%0a>     is stored. The electronic safe itself should preferably have%0a>     accountability and logging features built-in with seperate access%0a>     codes for multiple users of that safe.%0a> %0a> %0a205,268c200,262%0a%3c ---------------------------------------------%0a%3c %0a%3c Rule 3%0a%3c ~~~~~~%0a%3c %0a%3c Rule 3 is a most important one and is something both the countermeasures%0a%3c technician as well as his client should keep in mind and previously%0a%3c discuss during the initial client contact. Although it does not suit%0a%3c every situation, but in many cases it would be wise not to be recognized%0a%3c as a countermeasures technician for obvious reasons.  One does not want%0a%3c to spook the eavesroppers into either shutting their devices off,%0a%3c pulling them out temporarily or at worst ``skipping town" never to be%0a%3c heard from, and unlikely to be caught.%0a%3c %0a%3c Q: How does a countermeasures technician arrive at his clients office in a discreet manner?%0a%3c %0a%3c When it is deemed necessary, a simple ``disguise" is in order.  The TSCM%0a%3c Tech should blend in to look like all other employees, he should look%0a%3c and act like all employees, and in fact NO EMPLOYEES except a select few%0a%3c should even know the TSCM techs are who they are.  The TSCM tech should%0a%3c arrive in a vehichle preferable a ``work" vehicle which can be disguised%0a%3c as either a maintenance or utility company vehicle.%0a%3c %0a%3c All equipment should be carried in, under concealment. This means that%0a%3c some type of discreet yet common bag should be used to carry the%0a%3c equipment in.  It is obviously suspicious for a person to carry in 5%0a%3c briefcases (some of them being oversized cases indicating to the%0a%3c eavesdropper that its no ``ordinary" briefcase) into a building.%0a%3c %0a%3c One tactic I have personally used myself when doing the occasional sweep%0a%3c for a client,  is to arrive in a borrowed van which bears the name of%0a%3c some maintenance company.  My typical motife is to arrive as a%0a%3c ``painter" and when I enter the office if its a large office I announce%0a%3c myself as such to the secretary. This of course must be made clear in%0a%3c advance to the client so that the secretary knows that the  ``painter"%0a%3c (or ``plumber" or ``carpentry contractor" will arrive), again it should%0a%3c be stressed that not even secretaries should be made aware of the TSCM%0a%3c Techs identity or purpose of visit.  All equipment I carry in discreetly%0a%3c in a  painters spackle bag which is just large enough for most of my%0a%3c sweep gear. And for my spectrum analyzer which is too large for the%0a%3c spackle bag, I just haul that into the office discreetly wrapped up in a%0a%3c large painters cloth tarp. %0a%3c %0a%3c Usually I strip the plates off of the van and I remove the inspection%0a%3c and registration sticker so as to avoid being ``checked-out" by an LN%0a%3c agent who may find your van ``suspicous".  This in actuallity IS NOT THE%0a%3c IDEAL METHOD. I merely do that for convenience purposes.  (because I am%0a%3c not rich I cant afford multiple vans and vehicles registered to multiple%0a%3c legitimate ``ghost" companies which all must pay taxes and be registered%0a%3c with the state you do business in.) In fact its better to arrive in a%0a%3c van which  has license plates and registration which is legitimate as%0a%3c well as the company logo painted on the side of the truck belonging to%0a%3c an established legal business. This provides a better degree of cover.%0a%3c Although it is very very rare, it should likewise not be considered out%0a%3c of the question that an LN might ckeck out the validity of your company%0a%3c (a simple check of the yellow pages should turn up your company name.%0a%3c and if not...suspicion.)  It doesnt take a genius likewise to figure out%0a%3c that if you see a white van marked  ``Acme Painting Company" parked in%0a%3c front of your target building which you are eavesdropping upon, you%0a%3c should become suspicious.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c > (4) Assume that the eavesdropper can maintain a low vulnerability status when he is not listening.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> %0a> (3) Rule 3 is a most important one and is something both the countermeasures%0a>     technician as well as his client should keep in mind and previously%0a>     discuss during the initial client contact. Although it does not%0a>     suit every situation, but in many cases it would be wise not to%0a>     be recognized as a countermeasures technician for obvious reasons.%0a>     One does not want to spook the eavesroppers into either shutting their%0a>     devices off, pulling them out temporarily or at worst ``skipping town"%0a>     never to be heard from, and unlikely to be caught.%0a> %0a>  How does a countermeasures technician arrive at his clients office%0a>  in a discreet manner?%0a> %0a>     When it is deemed necessary, a simple ``disguise" is in order.%0a>     The TSCM Tech should blend in to look like all other employees,%0a>     he should look and act like all employees, and in fact NO EMPLOYEES%0a>     except a select few should even know the TSCM techs are who they are.%0a>     The TSCM tech should arrive in a vehichle preferable a ``work"%0a>     vehicle which can be disguised as either a maintenance or utility%0a>     company vehicle.%0a> %0a>     All equipment should be carried in, under concealment. This means%0a>     that some type of discreet yet common bag should be used to%0a>     carry the equipment in.  It is obviously suspicious for a person%0a>     to carry in 5 briefcases (some of them being oversized cases indicating%0a>     to the eavesdropper that its no ``ordinary" briefcase) into a building.%0a> %0a>  One tactic I have personally used myself when doing the occasional%0a>  sweep for a client,  is to arrive in a borrowed van which bears the%0a>  name of some maintenance company.  My typical motife is to arrive as%0a>  a ``painter" and when I enter the office if its a large office I announce%0a>  myself as such to the secretary. This of course must be made clear in%0a>  advance to the client so that the secretary knows that the  ``painter"%0a>  (or ``plumber" or ``carpentry contractor" will arrive), again it should%0a>  be stressed that not even secretaries should be made aware of the TSCM%0a>  Techs identity or purpose of visit.  All equipment I carry in discreetly%0a>  in a  painters spackle bag which is just large enough for most of%0a>  my sweep gear. And for my spectrum analyzer which is too large for the%0a>  spackle bag, I just haul that into the office discreetly wrapped up%0a>  in a large painters cloth tarp. %0a> %0a>  Usually I strip the plates off of the van and I remove the inspection%0a>  and registration sticker so as to avoid being ``checked-out" by an%0a>  LN agent who may find your van ``suspicous".  This in actuallity IS NOT%0a>  THE IDEAL METHOD. I merely do that for convenience purposes.%0a>  (because I am not rich I cant afford multiple vans and vehicles%0a>  registered to multiple legitimate ``ghost" companies which all must%0a>  pay taxes and be registered with the state you do business in.)%0a>  In fact its better to arrive in a van which  has license plates%0a>  and registration which is legitimate as well as the company%0a>  logo painted on the side of the truck belonging to an established%0a>  legal business. This provides a better degree of cover.%0a>  Although it is very very rare, it should likewise not be considered%0a>  out of the question that an LN might ckeck out the validity of%0a>  your company (a simple check of the yellow pages should turn up your%0a>  company name. and if not...suspicion.)  It doesnt take a genius%0a>  likewise to figure out that if you see a white van marked  ``Acme Painting%0a>  Company" parked in front of your target building which you are%0a>  eavesdropping upon, you should become suspicious.%0a> %0a> (4) Assume that the eavesdropper can maintain a low vulnerability status%0a>     when he is not listening.%0a> %0a274,275c268,269%0a%3c  * shutting the taps or bugs off remotely  (and)%0a%3c  * having an LN agent remove the taps/bugs after they are%0a---%0a>  [1] shutting the taps or bugs off remotely  (and)%0a>  [2] having an LN agent remove the taps/bugs after they are%0a281,282c275,276%0a%3c '''(5) Assume that the eavesdropper is guarding the NLJD band of frequencies.'''%0a%3c %0a---%0a> (5) Assume that the eavesdropper is guarding the NLJD band of frequencies.%0a> %0a332,333c326,328%0a%3c '''(6) Assume that the eavesdropper is watching for sweep receiver radiation.'''%0a%3c %0a---%0a> %0a> (6) Assume that the eavesdropper is watching for sweep receiver radiation.%0a> %0a360,434c355,467%0a%3c Moscow Rules for Telephone System Inspections%0a%3c ---------------------------------------------%0a%3c %0a%3c # Assume that the eavesdropper is listening to room sounds through the telephone instrument until tests prove otherwise.%0a%3c %0a%3c # Assume that the eavesdropper is listening across the line when the line is active.%0a%3c %0a%3c # Assume that the eavesdropper may be monitoring the line when it is inactive.%0a%3c %0a%3c # Assume that the eavesdropper is monitoring the line to detect TDR and RF tracing signals.%0a%3c %0a%3c Moscow Rules for Telephone System Inspections:%0a%3c ----------------------------------------------%0a%3c %0a%3c # The eavesdropper has a variety of techniques at his disposal which enable him to listen to 'room sounds' ("room audio" [note 1]) from a remote location. I will not discuss that in detail, because all the techniques involved in telephone and wireline attacks could fill an entire book in itself.  Generally however, their are two main techniques that could be employed. [Their are actually another 3 or 4 techniques but I shant get into discussing those for the sake of brevity.]%0a%3c %0a%3c ## 'Hot-miked telephone' otherwise called a 'Hot-On-Hook telephone' is one method, which involves modifying an actual telephone which is in a targets location (in reality, the targets phone itself is not modified, but an identical replacement is brought in and switched with the original [this technique of switching phones of course warrants caution as the target could possibly notice the difference between the two by noting scuff marks, etc. that were on the original phone]. The modification consists of a circuit that will allow the eavesdropper to listen to room sounds while the phone is still ``on-hook". The modification ``drops-out" once the phone is picked up for use and is brought ``off-hook" (in which case, the eavesdropper would then have a seperate circuit which could monitor the phone conversation.%0a%3c %0a%3c ## The second most common method is called an ``infinity transmitter", which in the 'olden days' circa 1960/70 was called a ``harmonica bug".  This is a slight variation of the hot-miked telephone. It is similar in that it allows a person to listen to room audio from a remote location, however the system employed need not be part of the actual telephone. The device could be hidden anywhere along the phone line in close proximity to the target where a seperate microphone can listen to room audio which is then sent through the phone lines while the phone is 'on-hook'. When the phone is lifted 'off-hook', the device drops-out. The device is activated remotely by the eavesdropper by simply calling the targets phone line and then activating the device.%0a%3c %0a%3c Room sounds could also be monitored by simply placing a microphone%0a%3c across any line pair, preferably a line pair which is not currently%0a%3c activated for phone useage (ie: the second yellow-black pair.) This%0a%3c would allow constant monitoring of the room audio even when the target%0a%3c uses the phone (which would be on line pair 1 (red-green) and thusly%0a%3c would not conflict. The microphone could either generate its own signal%0a%3c 9which has the disadvantage of being easier to detect because the%0a%3c microphone transmits constantly , or could use a microphone element%0a%3c which requires an external voltage such as in a carbon mic.  In the case%0a%3c of carbon microphones, the eavesdropper need only apply a small voltage%0a%3c to the line and the microphone will activate sending intercepted audio%0a%3c down the line. The device has the advantage that it is slightly harder%0a%3c to detect (especially inadvertently) because the unit only operates when%0a%3c the eavesdropper has the device activated.  Countermeasures technicians%0a%3c can find the device (in its simplest form) easy enough by just applying%0a%3c voltage to the line. But more sophisticated set-ups would utilize a%0a%3c 4-layer diode, SCR, or a reverse polarity configuration or some other%0a%3c method to hinder and thwart detection.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''(2) Rule 2 is fairly obvious and needs little explanation. Always%0a%3c assume that a phone line can be, or currently is being monitored.'''%0a%3c %0a%3c It is very important for the laymen to make the distinction between the%0a%3c two facts in the above statement which are:%0a%3c %0a%3c * the phone/line ``could" be tapped.%0a%3c * the phone/line ``is being" tapped.%0a%3c %0a%3c It does not make one paranoid to come to the conclusion and realization%0a%3c that a phone ``could" be tapped. It merely makes one alert and an%0a%3c informed individual.  That does not mean that one should insist that a%0a%3c line ``is" tapped, but it should simply be considered a possibilty which%0a%3c one must take into consideration and act accordingly on.%0a%3c %0a%3c Thusly, if one conducts confidential business in which it would be of%0a%3c important consequence to keep the conversation from prying ears of the%0a%3c eavesdropper, one should always employ end-to-end encryption through the%0a%3c use of telephone/fascimile ``scramblers". [note 2]%0a%3c %0a%3c One must make the decision for themselves regarding what is to be kept%0a%3c secret and what can be disclosed, and you must come to some sort of plan%0a%3c of action regarding what the different levels of confidentiality are.%0a%3c Some secrets are worth keeping more than others. In fact one might even%0a%3c say some secrets are so great that you should not disclose them to%0a%3c anyone ever. That would be the ultimate form of security. As an example,%0a%3c if you had just murdered someone, obviously any sane individual should%0a%3c not announce that over the phone lines, no matter how secure you feel%0a%3c that phone line is. Because their is no degree of security which is%0a%3c worth 25 years in prison or death. Even encryption (phone scramblers)%0a%3c should not be considered secure in such cases as they can be compromised%0a%3c rather easily by simply bypassing the encryption altogether through%0a%3c modification by the eavesdropper, or by simply liberating the code keys%0a%3c from the unit (which is a simple task with some encryption units while%0a%3c alot more difficult in the better units.)%0a%3c %0a---%0a> %0a> %0a> MOSCOW RULES FOR TELEPHONE SYSTEM INSPECTIONS%0a> =============================================%0a> %0a> (1) Assume that the eavesdropper is listening to room sounds through%0a>     the telephone instrument until tests prove otherwise.%0a> %0a> (2) Assume that the eavesdropper is listening across the%0a>     line when the line is active.%0a> %0a> (3) Assume that the eavesdropper may be monitoring the%0a>     line when it is inactive.%0a> %0a> (4) Assume that the eavesdropper is monitoring the line%0a>     to detect TDR and RF tracing signals.%0a> %0a> %0a> %0a> MOSCOW RULES FOR TELEPHONE SYSTEM INSPECTIONS:%0a> %0a> (1) The eavesdropper has a variety of techniques at his disposal which%0a>     enable him to listen to 'room sounds' ("room audio" [note 1]) from a%0a>     remote location. I will not discuss that in detail, because all%0a>     the techniques involved in telephone and wireline attacks could fill%0a>     an entire book in itself.%0a>     Generally however, their are two main techniques that could be%0a>     employed. [Their are actually another 3 or 