       across any line pair, preferably a line pair which is not currently%0a>       activated for phone useage (ie: the second yellow-black pair.)%0a>       This would allow constant monitoring of the room audio even when the%0a>       target uses the phone (which would be on line pair 1 (red-green)%0a>       and thusly would not conflict. The microphone could either generate%0a>       its own signal 9which has the disadvantage of being easier to detect%0a>       because the microphone transmits constantly , or could use a microphone%0a>       element which requires an external voltage such as in a carbon mic.%0a>       In the case of carbon microphones, the eavesdropper need only apply%0a>       a small voltage to the line and the microphone will activate sending%0a>       intercepted audio down the line. The device has the advantage that it%0a>       is slightly harder to detect (especially inadvertently) because the unit%0a>       only operates when the eavesdropper has the device activated.%0a>       Countermeasures technicians can find the device (in its simplest form)%0a>       easy enough by just applying voltage to the line. But more sophisticated%0a>       set-ups would utilize a 4-layer diode, SCR, or a reverse polarity%0a>       configuration or some other method to hinder and thwart detection.%0a> %0a> (2) Rule 2 is fairly obvious and needs little explanation. Always assume%0a>     that a phone line can be, or currently is being monitored.%0a> %0a>     It is very important for the laymen to make the distinction between%0a>     the two facts in the above statement which are:%0a> %0a>          [a] the phone/line ``could" be tapped.%0a>          [b] the phone/line ``is being" tapped.%0a> %0a>     It does not make one paranoid to come to the conclusion and realization%0a>     that a phone ``could" be tapped. It merely makes one alert and an%0a>     informed individual.  That does not mean that one should insist%0a>     that a line ``is" tapped, but it should simply be considered a possibilty%0a>     which one must take into consideration and act accordingly on.%0a> %0a>     Thusly, if one conducts confidential business in which it would be%0a>     of important consequence to keep the conversation from prying ears%0a>     of the eavesdropper, one should always employ end-to-end encryption%0a>     through the use of telephone/fascimile ``scramblers". [note 2]%0a> %0a>     One must make the decision for themselves regarding what is to%0a>     be kept secret and what can be disclosed, and you must come to%0a>     some sort of plan of action regarding what the different levels%0a>     of confidentiality are. Some secrets are worth keeping more than%0a>     others. In fact one might even say some secrets are so great that%0a>     you should not disclose them to anyone ever. That would be the%0a>     ultimate form of security. As an example, if you had just%0a>     murdered someone, obviously any sane individual should not announce%0a>     that over the phone lines, no matter how secure you feel that phone%0a>     line is. Because their is no degree of security which is worth%0a>     25 years in prison or death. Even encryption (phone scramblers)%0a>     should not be considered secure in such cases as they can be%0a>     compromised rather easily by simply bypassing the encryption%0a>     altogether through modification by the eavesdropper, or by simply%0a>     liberating the code keys from the unit (which is a simple task with%0a>     some encryption units while alot more difficult in the better units.)%0a> %0a484,651c517,690%0a%3c When dealing with recording telephone calls, a device is used which%0a%3c monitors the voltage on the line for off-hook/on-hook conditions and%0a%3c then activates a special tape recorder (with a remote activation jack)%0a%3c when the phone goes off-hook. [although a more clever eavesdropper would%0a%3c not use such a device but would rather use a VOX (voice [sound level]%0a%3c activated unit as opposed a voltage sensing unit which can actually be%0a%3c ``tricked" as well as ``detected" alot more easily which should be%0a%3c coupled to an inductive pick-up coil (or at the least a high-impedance%0a%3c capacitively coupled interface). VOX units too also have their problems,%0a%3c namely they can have havoc wreaked upon them by the use of masking%0a%3c devices or ``telephone security units" which are now widely sold on the%0a%3c market for a couple hundred dollars. These telephone security units have%0a%3c the ability to defeat most simple eavesdropping methods utilizing%0a%3c techniques such as masking as well as ``Line Balancing". The latter%0a%3c technique of balancing performed by raising the voltage, while the%0a%3c current is simultaneously lowered.  Such a technique does not interfere%0a%3c with the PSTN Central Office and will give the user a dial-tone when the%0a%3c line is raised off-hook(600 Ohms) and will thusly defeats most voltage%0a%3c activated devices such as simple telephone tap transmistters as well as%0a%3c drop-out relays (telephone recorder controllers).%0a%3c %0a%3c The foolish individual could conclude that if most eavesdroppers used a%0a%3c voltage activated device that only recorded audio when the phone was%0a%3c ``off-hook", then the line should be secured in an ``on-hook" condition.%0a%3c Example, a person could then transmit his voice within the household or%0a%3c office while the phone was still ``on-hook" using a relatively simple%0a%3c circuit to do that and ``supposedly" that would alow for safe%0a%3c conversation, and it would be safe ``if" a voltage activated telephone%0a%3c recording adapter was used.  However, many eavesdroppers (sophisticated%0a%3c ones) may be a bit more clever than that. The clever eavesdropper may%0a%3c monitor a line pair even when it is inactive (such as when a phone is%0a%3c ``on-hook".) This would allow the eavesdropper to hear  ``AUDIO" [note%0a%3c 1] even when the phone is off-hook.  Note I use the word AUDIO very%0a%3c carefully. Because in such an instance, the eavsdropper may NOT just be%0a%3c listening to secret conversations which occur ``on-hook" but he may be%0a%3c listening to other audio which could be a potential threat to the%0a%3c eavesdropper such a the sounds of audible line tracing, ultrasonic line%0a%3c tracing or ultrasonic voice modulation, as well as RF tracing, and%0a%3c lastly the eavesdropper could be looking for the signals emmenating from%0a%3c a TDR (see rule #4 explanation).%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (4) The last rule is a rather esoterical one which is of more concern to%0a%3c the countermeasures technician who is performing the search as opposed%0a%3c to concern of your ordinary individual or businessman concerned with the%0a%3c rules to insuring privacy.%0a%3c %0a%3c Rule #4 is just a follow up to rule #3 which states that an eavesdropper%0a%3c could possibly be monitoring the inactive line pair. In rule #4 we get%0a%3c specific in saying that an eavesdropper may be looking for RF signals or%0a%3c TDR signals which may be an indication of a countermeasures ``sweep"%0a%3c which is being conducted. This should concern the eavesdropper for%0a%3c obvious reasons, which are that he could possibly be discovered very%0a%3c soon if the technician is a competant one, or if the eavesdroppers%0a%3c set-up is crude or poorly installed in which case it could possibly be%0a%3c detected.%0a%3c %0a%3c I have already explained ultrasonic and RF tracing above in rule 3, so%0a%3c I'll just deal with TDR's.%0a%3c %0a%3c A TDR is common abbreviation for a device known as a Time Domain%0a%3c Reflectometer. You pronounce the units name by simply saying the%0a%3c letters.   ``T" - ``D" - ``R".%0a%3c %0a%3c The TDR is a common tool of anyone who works exensively with wires (or%0a%3c fiber optic cabling) of any type. The type of TDR we are discussing is%0a%3c only for the ``wire" and not ``fiber optic" type.  TDR's are used by%0a%3c cable company technicians, computer network technicians, telephone%0a%3c lineman or repair personell, as well as surveillance countermeasures%0a%3c technicians.%0a%3c %0a%3c A TDR is a device (usually a hand-held size device although slightly%0a%3c larger and more powerfull bench-top units are available) which emits a%0a%3c mild powered signal into a wire pair. This signal gets sent down a wire%0a%3c pair, or through a coaxial cable and gets partially reflected off of any%0a%3c discontinuity on the line pair. Herein, I'll refer to any discontinuous%0a%3c reflections as an ``anomaly" on the wire. I use the word as opposed to%0a%3c discontinuity (because its easier to type) and because much like an%0a%3c anomoly it is indicative of the unknown. And thats what your looking for%0a%3c when doing a TSCM TDR sweep of a wire pair.  Your looking for unknown or%0a%3c strange situations.  It is these anomalies which the technician is%0a%3c looking for which are a possible source of the problem (or could even%0a%3c indicate that everything is normal if their is supposed to be an anomoly%0a%3c at some point).%0a%3c %0a%3c The word ``anomaly" is a generic term which refers to anything on the%0a%3c line which will interfere with the signal going through the line.  To%0a%3c put it another way, it is something which causes part of the signal to%0a%3c literally reflect backwards from the point of origin instead of%0a%3c traveling freely and smoothly through the wire.%0a%3c %0a%3c This ``reflection" of the signal is what the TDR is looking to receive%0a%3c after it emits the original pulse. The reflection which could be of%0a%3c varying degrees of intensity depending on how large the anomaly is.  The%0a%3c larger the anomaly, the larger the reflection, and occasionaly that%0a%3c means the bigger the problem. Ideally the signal is supposed to travel%0a%3c through the wire impeded as little as possible.  Anomalies are caused by%0a%3c a wide variety of things too great to discuss here. They can be caused%0a%3c by imperfections in the wire itself, they can be caused by splices in%0a%3c the line, they can be caused by ``connectors" on a wireline which join 2%0a%3c wires together or a wire to a piece of equipment. Anomalies can be%0a%3c caused by ``termination plugs" which are a dummy loads placed at the end%0a%3c of a unused wirepair. Anomalies can also be caused by physical hardware%0a%3c on the line such as splitters, filters, junction boxes, 66/110blocks,%0a%3c entrance bridges, and the list can go on and on.%0a%3c %0a%3c The countermeasures technician is primarily interested in looking for%0a%3c things such as splices on the line which could be indicative of a%0a%3c telephone tap.  Keep in mind, that the word ``splice" does not%0a%3c necessarily preclude that a line was physically ``spliced" (ie: cut and%0a%3c then re-connected.) It also can imply a simple ``tap" on the line where%0a%3c one wire (alligator clip, etc.) is touching upon the original wireline.%0a%3c TDR's have a typical range of 1,000 - 10,000 feet. A typical handheld%0a%3c TDR used by computer network installers will have ranges of 1,000 - 2k%0a%3c feet. Countermeasures technicians often utilize slightly more powerfull%0a%3c models extending 2,000 - 5,000 feet so they can have the ability to%0a%3c trace large amounts of wires present in office buildings. And benchmodel%0a%3c units which are usually the most powerfull (although some handheld units%0a%3c are capable of such) can extend upwards of 10,000 or more feet.  These%0a%3c units can pinpoint  ``flaws" or ``anomalies" on a wireline to a%0a%3c resolution of millimeters which makes them damned accurate devices which%0a%3c can tell you exactly where the flaw is down the line. (typically however%0a%3c in high powered devices the resolution is limited to feet or meters).%0a%3c %0a%3c The TDR is most effective when it is used on a routine basis and a%0a%3c day-to-day (or more likely week-to-week or moth-to-month) comparison can%0a%3c be made between the different or same results.  Ideally, the results of%0a%3c the TDR should always be the same.  Should a result be significantly%0a%3c different on one occasion, or something appears to have been%0a%3c spliced/tapped onto the line it will be readily apparent.%0a%3c %0a%3c Of course for the TDR test to be most effective, it should be realized%0a%3c that the initial tests of the TDR must be done when the line was%0a%3c ``clean".  If the line was tapped in the first place the first time you%0a%3c tested it, then all subsequent comparisons thereafter are of little use%0a%3c because you cant compare a ``clean" like with a ``tapped" line.%0a%3c %0a%3c However, that factor doesnt render a TDR test completely useless.  One%0a%3c does not necessarily rely solely on the technique of comparison from one%0a%3c time to another.  Other methods exist for using the TDR which are a%0a%3c combination of tracing the line physically with the TDR from the demarc%0a%3c point inwards to the telephone instruments and physically searching the%0a%3c line for taps/splices in conjunction with the use of voltmeters or%0a%3c telephone analyzers to search for imbalanced loops, or imbalanced lines%0a%3c to ground, crossed line pairs as well as suspicious line impedances.%0a%3c Likewise, the search should occur from the demarc point outwards towards%0a%3c the telephone company as far as one can go. The search should extend out%0a%3c the end of the customers property,  but a countermeasures technician who%0a%3c does not mind breaking a few laws might feel free to extend the test%0a%3c point up to the neighborhood cross connect cabinets where the%0a%3c distribution cable meets the feeders.%0a%3c %0a%3c [note 1]%0a%3c %0a%3c In surveillance lingo, the word ``AUDIO" is often used as opposed to the%0a%3c word ``SOUND" or ``CONVERSATION". The meanings are almost synonymous,%0a%3c but their is a slight difference.  The word ``audio" is used because it%0a%3c denotes any type of intelligence which could be collected and is not%0a%3c limited to intercepting spoken conversations (spoken words). %0a%3c %0a%3c [note 2]%0a%3c %0a%3c Even encryption (phone scramblers) should not be considered secure as%0a%3c they can be compromised rather easily by simply bypassing the encryption%0a%3c altogether through modification of the telephone instrument by the%0a%3c eavesdropper, or by simply liberating the code keys from the unit.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a---%0a>     When dealing with recording telephone calls, a device is used which%0a>     monitors the voltage on the line for off-hook/on-hook conditions%0a>     and then activates a special tape recorder (with a remote activation%0a>     jack) when the phone goes off-hook. [although a more clever eavesdropper%0a>     would not use such a device but would rather use a VOX (voice%0a>     [sound level] activated unit as opposed a voltage sensing unit which%0a>     can actually be ``tricked" as well as ``detected" alot more easily%0a>     which should be coupled to an inductive pick-up coil (or at the least%0a>     a high-impedance capacitively coupled interface). VOX units too also%0a>     have their problems, namely they can have havoc wreaked upon them%0a>     by the use of masking devices or ``telephone security units" which are%0a>     now widely sold on the market for a couple hundred dollars. These%0a>     telephone security units have the ability to defeat most simple%0a>     eavesdropping methods utilizing  techniques such as masking as well%0a>     as ``Line Balancing". The latter technique of balancing performed by%0a>     raising the voltage, while the current is simultaneously lowered.%0a>     Such a technique does not interfere with the PSTN Central Office and%0a>     will give the user a dial-tone when the line is raised off-hook(600 Ohms)%0a>     and will thusly defeats most voltage activated devices such as simple%0a>     telephone tap transmistters as well as drop-out relays (telephone%0a>     recorder controllers).%0a> %0a>     The foolish individual could conclude that if most eavesdroppers%0a>     used a voltage activated device that only recorded audio when the%0a>     phone was ``off-hook", then the line should be secured in an ``on-hook"%0a>     condition. Example, a person could then transmit his voice within%0a>     the household or office while the phone was still ``on-hook" using a%0a>     relatively simple circuit to do that and ``supposedly" that would%0a>     alow for safe conversation, and it would be safe ``if" a voltage%0a>     activated telephone recording adapter was used.%0a>     However, many eavesdroppers (sophisticated ones) may be a bit more%0a>     clever than that. The clever eavesdropper may monitor a line pair%0a>     even when it is inactive (such as when a phone is ``on-hook".)%0a>     This would allow the eavesdropper to hear  ``AUDIO" [note 1]%0a>     even when the phone is off-hook.  Note I use the word AUDIO very%0a>     carefully. Because in such an instance, the eavsdropper may NOT%0a>     just be listening to secret conversations which occur ``on-hook"%0a>     but he may be listening to other audio which could be a potential%0a>     threat to the eavesdropper such a the sounds of audible line tracing,%0a>     ultrasonic line tracing or ultrasonic voice modulation, as well%0a>     as RF tracing, and lastly the eavesdropper could be looking for%0a>     the signals emmenating from a TDR (see rule #4 explanation).%0a> %0a> %0a> (4) The last rule is a rather esoterical one which is of more concern%0a>     to the countermeasures technician who is performing the search%0a>     as opposed to concern of your ordinary individual or businessman%0a>     concerned with the rules to insuring privacy.%0a> %0a>     Rule #4 is just a follow up to rule #3 which states that an eavesdropper%0a>     could possibly be monitoring the inactive line pair. In rule #4 we%0a>     get specific in saying that an eavesdropper may be looking for%0a>     RF signals or TDR signals which may be an indication of a countermeasures%0a>     ``sweep" which is being conducted. This should concern the eavesdropper%0a>     for obvious reasons, which are that he could possibly be discovered%0a>     very soon if the technician is a competant one, or if the eavesdroppers%0a>     set-up is crude or poorly installed in which case it could possibly%0a>     be detected.%0a> %0a>     I have already explained ultrasonic and RF tracing above in rule 3,%0a>     so I'll just deal with TDR's.%0a> %0a>     A TDR is common abbreviation for a device known as a Time Domain%0a>     Reflectometer. You pronounce the units name by simply saying the%0a>     letters.   ``T" - ``D" - ``R".%0a> %0a>     The TDR is a common tool of anyone who works exensively with wires%0a>     (or fiber optic cabling) of any type. The type of TDR we are discussing%0a>     is only for the ``wire" and not ``fiber optic" type.%0a>     TDR's are used by cable company technicians, computer network%0a>     technicians, telephone lineman or repair personell, as well as%0a>     surveillance countermeasures technicians.%0a> %0a>     A TDR is a device (usually a hand-held size device although slightly%0a>     larger and more powerfull bench-top units are available) which emits%0a>     a mild powered signal into a wire pair. This signal gets sent down%0a>     a wire pair, or through a coaxial cable and gets partially reflected%0a>     off of any discontinuity on the line pair. Herein, I'll refer to any%0a>     discontinuous reflections as an ``anomaly" on the wire. I use the word%0a>     as opposed to discontinuity (because its easier to type) and because%0a>     much like an anomoly it is indicative of the unknown. And thats what%0a>     your looking for when doing a TSCM TDR sweep of a wire pair.%0a>     Your looking for unknown or strange situations.%0a>     It is these anomalies which the technician is looking for which are a%0a>     possible source of the problem (or could even indicate that everything%0a>     is normal if their is supposed to be an anomoly at some point).%0a> %0a>     The word ``anomaly" is a generic term which refers to anything on the%0a>     line which will interfere with the signal going through the line.%0a>     To put it another way, it is something which causes part of the signal to%0a>     literally reflect backwards from the point of origin instead of traveling%0a>     freely and smoothly through the wire.%0a> %0a>     This ``reflection" of the signal is what the TDR is looking to receive%0a>     after it emits the original pulse. The reflection which could be of%0a>     varying degrees of intensity depending on how large the anomaly is.%0a>     The larger the anomaly, the larger the reflection, and occasionaly that%0a>     means the bigger the problem. Ideally the signal is supposed to travel%0a>     through the wire impeded as little as possible.  Anomalies are caused%0a>     by a wide variety of things too great to discuss here. They can be%0a>     caused by imperfections in the wire itself, they can be caused by%0a>     splices in the line, they can be caused by ``connectors" on a wireline%0a>     which join 2 wires together or a wire to a piece of equipment. Anomalies%0a>     can be caused by ``termination plugs" which are a dummy loads placed%0a>     at the end of a unused wirepair. Anomalies can also be caused by%0a>     physical hardware on the line such as splitters, filters, junction boxes,%0a>     66/110blocks, entrance bridges, and the list can go on and on.%0a> %0a>     The countermeasures technician is primarily interested in looking for%0a>     things such as splices on the line which could be indicative of a%0a>     telephone tap.  Keep in mind, that the word ``splice" does not necessarily%0a>     preclude that a line was physically ``spliced" (ie: cut and then%0a>     re-connected.) It also can imply a simple ``tap" on the line where one%0a>     wire (alligator clip, etc.) is touching upon the original wireline.%0a>     TDR's have a typical range of 1,000 - 10,000 feet. A typical handheld%0a>     TDR used by computer network installers will have ranges of 1,000 - 2k%0a>     feet. Countermeasures technicians often utilize slightly more powerfull%0a>     models extending 2,000 - 5,000 feet so they can have the ability to%0a>     trace large amounts of wires present in office buildings. And benchmodel%0a>     units which are usually the most powerfull (although some handheld%0a>     units are capable of such) can extend upwards of 10,000 or more feet.%0a>     These units can pinpoint  ``flaws" or ``anomalies" on a wireline to%0a>     a resolution of millimeters which makes them damned accurate devices%0a>     which can tell you exactly where the flaw is down the line. (typically%0a>     however in high powered devices the resolution is limited to feet or%0a>     meters).%0a> %0a>     The TDR is most effective when it is used on a routine basis and a%0a>     day-to-day (or more likely week-to-week or moth-to-month) comparison%0a>     can be made between the different or same results.  Ideally, the%0a>     results of the TDR should always be the same.  Should a result be%0a>     significantly different on one occasion, or something appears to have%0a>     been spliced/tapped onto the line it will be readily apparent.%0a> %0a>     Of course for the TDR test to be most effective, it should be realized%0a>     that the initial tests of the TDR must be done when the line was ``clean".%0a>     If the line was tapped in the first place the first time you tested%0a>     it, then all subsequent comparisons thereafter are of little use because%0a>     you cant compare a ``clean" like with a ``tapped" line.%0a> %0a>     However, that factor doesnt render a TDR test completely useless.%0a>     One does not necessarily rely solely on the technique of comparison%0a>     from one time to another.  Other methods exist for using the TDR%0a>     which are a combination of tracing the line physically with the TDR%0a>     from the demarc point inwards to the telephone instruments and%0a>     physically searching the line for taps/splices in conjunction with%0a>     the use of voltmeters or telephone analyzers to search for%0a>     imbalanced loops, or imbalanced lines to ground, crossed line pairs%0a>     as well as suspicious line impedances.%0a>     Likewise, the search should occur from the demarc point outwards%0a>     towards the telephone company as far as one can go. The search should%0a>     extend out the end of the customers property,  but a countermeasures%0a>     technician who does not mind breaking a few laws might feel free%0a>     to extend the test point up to the neighborhood cross connect cabinets%0a>     where the distribution cable meets the feeders.%0a> %0a>                             [note 1]%0a> %0a>   In surveillance lingo, the word ``AUDIO" is often used as opposed to%0a>   the word ``SOUND" or ``CONVERSATION". The meanings are almost synonymous,%0a>   but their is a slight difference.  The word ``audio" is used because%0a>   it denotes any type of intelligence which could be collected and is%0a>   not limited to intercepting spoken conversations (spoken words). %0a> %0a>                             [note 2]%0a> %0a>   Even encryption (phone scramblers) should not be considered secure%0a>   as they can be compromised rather easily by simply bypassing the%0a>   encryption altogether through modification of the telephone instrument%0a>   by the eavesdropper, or by simply liberating the code keys from the unit.%0a> %0a> %0a> %0a> -----------------------------%0a653,654c692%0a%3c =============================%0a%3c %0a---%0a> -----------------------------%0a657c695%0a%3c How does this concern you if you don't run a company?%0a---%0a> How does this concern you if you dont run a company?%0a
