diff:1194006754:1194006754:=1,742d0%0a%3c * Relying on face-to-face meetings%0a%3c * Always being in a private setting when handing over items of value%0a%3c * Whenever carrying items of value (i.e. microfilm) carry them camouflaged for immediate discard. (The dead general was carrying his microfilm in a cigarette packet).%0a%3c * Use of sign and counter-sign to signal (pins, chalk) that surroundings have been reconnoitered and coast is clear to proceed to rendezvous%0a%3c * Use of dead letter drops, and other ``tradecraft"%0a%3c * Never traveling directly to a rendezvous, never taking a single taxi to destination%0a%3c %0a%3c And so on. I could not recommend Smiley's People and the two volumes of the ``Karla Trilogy" that came before it (Tinker, Tailor Soldier Spy and Honourable Schoolboy) more highly.%0a%3c %0a%3c  -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-%0a%3c                RULES FOR INSURING PRIVACY IN AN ORGANIZATION.%0a%3c                        CONSTANT AWARENESS OF THREATS.%0a%3c               -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-%0a%3c                              Written by: -Q-%0a%3c                             -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-%0a%3c %0a%3c The following is a brief abstract on the topic of privacy and the awareness%0a%3c of threats and vulnerabilities.  I shall in this text discuss some of the%0a%3c common rules that security experts and countermeasures technicians live by.%0a%3c %0a%3c I have found that the best set of rules published to date is by%0a%3c Glen H. Whidden which he draws upon from his 28 year career with the CIA.%0a%3c Mr. Whidden, noted as one of the countries most knowledgeable surveillance%0a%3c countermeasures experts details these rules in the books which his company%0a%3c Technical Services Agency (TSA) publishes.%0a%3c %0a%3c I shall simply reprint these rules from his book  "A GUIDEBOOK FOR THE%0a%3c BEGINNING SWEEPER".   Mr. Whidden has  lovingly given his rules a name,%0a%3c and that is:  "THE MOSCOW RULES".    I  dont  know what it specifically%0a%3c means.. Nothing really, just a clever slogan.. but anyway the rules are%0a%3c as follows.%0a%3c %0a%3c MOSCOW RULES FOR COUNTER ESPIONAGE INVESTIGATIONS%0a%3c =================================================%0a%3c (1) Assume that all LN's are hostile.%0a%3c (2) Assume that an approach by a non-LN is hostile until proven otherwise.%0a%3c (3) Assume that there is always hostile physical surveillance unless%0a%3c     counter-surveillance proves otherwise.%0a%3c (4) Assume that all telephone conversations are monitored by LN's.%0a%3c (5) Assume that all enclosed areas are bugged unless they are 'secure' rooms.%0a%3c (6) Assume that incoming and outgoing mail will be subject to hostile%0a%3c     examination.%0a%3c (7) Assume that anything that is left unattended will be subject to%0a%3c     examination by LN's.%0a%3c (8) Assume that locks left unguarded or unprotected will be manipulated%0a%3c     or bypased and the material they protect will be compromised.%0a%3c (9) Assume that simple traps will not deceive LN's.%0a%3c 10) Assume that any guard can be recruited by LN's or is himself%0a%3c     an LN agent.%0a%3c 11) Assume that a pair of guards can be recruited by LN's or are%0a%3c     themselves agents of LN's.%0a%3c %0a%3c MOSCOW RULES FOR COUNTERMEASURES INSPECTIONS%0a%3c =================================================%0a%3c (1) Assume that the eavesdropper is listening in the sensitve areas.%0a%3c (2) Assume that an eavesdropper has an agent near the sensitive area.%0a%3c (3) Assume that the eavesdropper is watching the entrances of the facility.%0a%3c (4) Assume that the eavesdropper can maintain a low vulnerability status%0a%3c     when he is not listening.%0a%3c (5) Assume that the eavesdropper is guarding the NLJD band of frequencies.%0a%3c (6) Assume that the eavesdropper is watching for sweep receiver radiation.%0a%3c %0a%3c TRANSLATION INTO ENGLISH%0a%3c ============================%0a%3c Mr Whidden, then goes onto explain what each one of the above rules%0a%3c means in detail, but it is rather long-winded and I wont reprint it%0a%3c in this text.  Most of the rules are very simpe to understand, but%0a%3c a few points warrant explanation which I'll put into my own words so%0a%3c I can explain it in more simplistic terms.%0a%3c %0a%3c First, Mr. Whidden uses the term  "LN" (which stands for Local National)%0a%3c which means a person who is indigenous to a specific area.  This term has%0a%3c a greater meaning in the field of world intelligence as it means a citizen%0a%3c of a foreign country who may be an agent or informer of that country or it%0a%3c may be a citizen of another country that you recruit as an "agent" or%0a%3c "asset" to work for you.  However, in the context of the Moscow Rules it%0a%3c is simply a term of convenience which is not nearly so grande. In such%0a%3c context of the rules it merely refers to a person who may work for an%0a%3c organization or a corporation who is either acting on their own accord or%0a%3c under the direction of others and the purpose of that individual is to%0a%3c infiltrate and or compromise the corporation or organization usually in a%0a%3c covert manner (such as to steal business secrets in industrial espionage),%0a%3c but can be done in an overt manner also if the intent is to destroy or cause%0a%3c harm or embarress the organization.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c MOSCOW RULES FOR COUNTER ESPIONAGE INVESTIGATIONS:%0a%3c (1) Rule 1 which states that you should assume that all LN's are hostile%0a%3c     roughly translates to the philosophy of   "trust nobody!"%0a%3c     This is extended to include the very person who hired you!%0a%3c     As unlikely as it may seem, if you look at the rules it is a very%0a%3c     logical conclusion, especially in a corporate situation.  It is%0a%3c     very common for the  "security department"  to be the one to request%0a%3c     that a TSCM countermeasures sweep be performed, this can be done%0a%3c     to please the bosses and make the executives feel that since the%0a%3c     sweep was done all the confidential conversations are secure.%0a%3c     In a real world situation it is likely that one or more individuals%0a%3c     in the 'security department' itself may be the actual perpetrator%0a%3c     and they thusly will be well aware of the search for eavesdropping%0a%3c     devices and they will have the ability to easily deactivate or remove%0a%3c     the clandestine devices before the search, wheras they can be replaced%0a%3c     promptly after the search was performed. This tactic of infiltration%0a%3c     not only gives the eavesdroppers the advatage of knowing when a sweep%0a%3c     is to be performed but also provides a form of 'cover' since the security%0a%3c     employee (really an LN "agent") will seem all the more legitimate%0a%3c     since he is the one that ordered the sweep.  One can reference%0a%3c     Moscow Rules 10 & 11 to realize that "guards" and "security" should%0a%3c     not usually be given 100 percent trust.  The "SWEEPER"  MUST obey%0a%3c     what the security staff says, even if the sweeper suspects the%0a%3c     guards or security staff as being the actual perpetrators, and once%0a%3c     actual proof is established to concurr that fact, the sweeper should%0a%3c     convey that possibility to some other person within the company who%0a%3c     the sweeper feels is trustworthy.%0a%3c %0a%3c (4) Rule 4 is an especially important one. Although it needs no elaboration,%0a%3c     I cannot stress how important it is NEVER EVER to discuss anything%0a%3c     sensitive over a telephone (that is even more so true if you have%0a%3c     a cordles or cellular phone).%0a%3c     Also, it should also be noted in my personal opinion, that not even%0a%3c     encrypted phones/faxes should be beyond suspicion. Their exists many%0a%3c     ways to defeat such encryption. The easiest is simply to compromise the%0a%3c     keys which is not a difficult task if your target is unaware. A simple%0a%3c     blag-bag job is all that is needed to either liberate the codes from%0a%3c     the encryption unit itself or from a locked safe or drawer which can%0a%3c     then be copied to floppy and the original code returned to its position%0a%3c     undisturbed.  Modern encryption units such as the STU phones do help%0a%3c     to some small extent to guard against such attacks by the uses of%0a%3c     "ignition or code keys" which can be physically taken from the unit to%0a%3c     help secure the units key integrity, but their are ways around that.%0a%3c     Then of course, it is never beyond reason to doubt that the encryption%0a%3c     itself can be cracked if it is deemed a priority. This is a mere simple%0a%3c     task which can be done in a half a second if your using weak encryption%0a%3c     on your phone such as simple "inversion" chips or other simple%0a%3c     encryption units which are widly sold in catalogs.  It is also not%0a%3c     out of reason to realize that even DES is not safe anymore, although%0a%3c     its a hell of alot safer than "inversion chips" which can be cracked%0a%3c     with a $50 kit available in the classifieds of most electronic magazines.%0a%3c %0a%3c (5) Rule 5 states that all conversations should be considered vulnerable%0a%3c     unless conducted in a "secure" room.   Personally, I hold to the%0a%3c     philosophy that THEIR IS NO SUCH THING as a "secure" room, but then%0a%3c     one must realize that this is reality and you cannot be completely%0a%3c     paranoid.%0a%3c %0a%3c     A "secure" room is a complicated term to define as their are many%0a%3c     degrees of what is considered "secure".  The ultimate "secure" room%0a%3c     would be completely RF (Radio Frequency) proof and would thusly%0a%3c     attenuate completely all RF transmissions from "bugs", but the%0a%3c     security must be extended to insure that no wires/fiber enter the%0a%3c     room or leave the room as they can carry clandestine signals hidden%0a%3c     on that wire (or at the very least all wires must be monitored for%0a%3c     hidden signals). The room must have no loudspeakers which can act%0a%3c     as microphones, the room preferable would have no windows and if it%0a%3c     did would attenute any Infrared light so as to protect against%0a%3c     RF/IR transmitters. And lastly the room would be acoustically secure%0a%3c     which means their would be virtually no acoustic leakage (in otherwords%0a%3c     no sound could be heard on the other side of the wall using any types%0a%3c     of devices such as microphones and high powered amplifiers.)%0a%3c     Also, to be acoustically secure, the room should have sufficient%0a%3c     random masking signals present and continuously fed into the secure%0a%3c     room. Their should be several of such masking generators in use%0a%3c     at different points in the room and in addition all plenums and%0a%3c     air vents should be masked as well. In addition, the walls as well%0a%3c     as any windows should be masked using a transducer element which%0a%3c     vibrates all windows and walls in a random fashion to further defeat%0a%3c     any clandestine listening devices such as contact microphones, spike%0a%3c     or tube microphones which are drilled into the wall from the opposite%0a%3c     non-guarded side, as well as techniques of 'laser/microwave pick-off'.%0a%3c %0a%3c (8) Rule 8 also warrants elaboration. All mechanical locking mechanisms%0a%3c     are easily bypassed by persons with experience in such fields -%0a%3c     which very often includes an eavesdropper himself - or on occasion,%0a%3c     an eavesdropper may have a  "keyman"  which is a person who is%0a%3c     an entry specialist (called "quick-entry" in the locksmithing field).%0a%3c %0a%3c     To properly secure a facility electronic locking mechanisms should%0a%3c     be used which are much harder (yet not impossible to defeat).%0a%3c     Preferably a secure installation should go beyond simple electronic%0a%3c     locking mechanisms (such as key card system connected to an%0a%3c     electric strike). A complete access system must be incorporated%0a%3c     with full provisions for software logging of all entries and%0a%3c     exits, as well as "anti-passback" protection to further enhance%0a%3c     accountability and security and tracking.%0a%3c %0a%3c     All safes should be of the electronic type, NOT the mechanical%0a%3c     combination type of yesteryear.  It is not a difficult task to%0a%3c     bypass combination safes nowadays.  The top expert safecrackers can%0a%3c     ply their trade in an hour to two hours time, and a device now exists%0a%3c     on the market which cracks safes automatically using a computer%0a%3c     controlled mechanism and does so in approximately 1 hour.%0a%3c     Electronic safes are virtually 100 percent secure and are the current%0a%3c     standard on all government facilities where classified information%0a%3c     is stored. The electronic safe itself should preferably have%0a%3c     accountability and logging features built-in with seperate access%0a%3c     codes for multiple users of that safe.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c MOSCOW RULES FOR COUNTERMEASURES INSPECTIONS:%0a%3c %0a%3c (3) Rule 3 is a most important one and is something both the countermeasures%0a%3c     technician as well as his client should keep in mind and previously%0a%3c     discuss during the initial client contact. Although it does not%0a%3c     suit every situation, but in many cases it would be wise not to%0a%3c     be recognized as a countermeasures technician for obvious reasons.%0a%3c     One does not want to spook the eavesroppers into either shutting their%0a%3c     devices off, pulling them out temporarily or at worst "skipping town"%0a%3c     never to be heard from, and unlikely to be caught.%0a%3c %0a%3c  How does a countermeasures technician arrive at his clients office%0a%3c  in a discreet manner?%0a%3c %0a%3c     When it is deemed necessary, a simple "disguise" is in order.%0a%3c     The TSCM Tech should blend in to look like all other employees,%0a%3c     he should look and act like all employees, and in fact NO EMPLOYEES%0a%3c     except a select few should even know the TSCM techs are who they are.%0a%3c     The TSCM tech should arrive in a vehichle preferable a "work"%0a%3c     vehicle which can be disguised as either a maintenance or utility%0a%3c     company vehicle.%0a%3c %0a%3c     All equipment should be carried in, under concealment. This means%0a%3c     that some type of discreet yet common bag should be used to%0a%3c     carry the equipment in.  It is obviously suspicious for a person%0a%3c     to carry in 5 briefcases (some of them being oversized cases indicating%0a%3c     to the eavesdropper that its no "ordinary" briefcase) into a building.%0a%3c %0a%3c  One tactic I have personally used myself when doing the occasional%0a%3c  sweep for a client,  is to arrive in a borrowed van which bears the%0a%3c  name of some maintenance company.  My typical motife is to arrive as%0a%3c  a "painter" and when I enter the office if its a large office I announce%0a%3c  myself as such to the secretary. This of course must be made clear in%0a%3c  advance to the client so that the secretary knows that the  "painter"%0a%3c  (or "plumber" or "carpentry contractor" will arrive), again it should%0a%3c  be stressed that not even secretaries should be made aware of the TSCM%0a%3c  Techs identity or purpose of visit.  All equipment I carry in discreetly%0a%3c  in a  painters spackle bag which is just large enough for most of%0a%3c  my sweep gear. And for my spectrum analyzer which is too large for the%0a%3c  spackle bag, I just haul that into the office discreetly wrapped up%0a%3c  in a large painters cloth tarp. %0a%3c %0a%3c  Usually I strip the plates off of the van and I remove the inspection%0a%3c  and registration sticker so as to avoid being "checked-out" by an%0a%3c  LN agent who may find your van "suspicous".  This in actuallity IS NOT%0a%3c  THE IDEAL METHOD. I merely do that for convenience purposes.%0a%3c  (because I am not rich I cant afford multiple vans and vehicles%0a%3c  registered to multiple legitimate "ghost" companies which all must%0a%3c  pay taxes and be registered with the state you do business in.)%0a%3c  In fact its better to arrive in a van which  has license plates%0a%3c  and registration which is legitimate as well as the company%0a%3c  logo painted on the side of the truck belonging to an established%0a%3c  legal business. This provides a better degree of cover.%0a%3c  Although it is very very rare, it should likewise not be considered%0a%3c  out of the question that an LN might ckeck out the validity of%0a%3c  your company (a simple check of the yellow pages should turn up your%0a%3c  company name.. and if not.... suspicion..)  It doesnt take a genius%0a%3c  likewise to figure out that if you see a white van marked  "Acme Painting%0a%3c  Company" parked in front of your target building which you are%0a%3c  eavesdropping upon, you should become suspicious.%0a%3c %0a%3c (4) Assume that the eavesdropper can maintain a low vulnerability status%0a%3c     when he is not listening.%0a%3c %0a%3c What rule number 4 deals with, is the eavesdroppers ability to make%0a%3c himself "invisible" to the TSCM Technician, Security Staff and his%0a%3c intended "targets" by various methods too detailed to describe here.%0a%3c %0a%3c This mainly includes 2 tactics..%0a%3c  [1] shutting the taps or bugs off remotely  (and)%0a%3c  [2] having an LN agent remove the taps/bugs after they are%0a%3c      no longer needed and then promptly replacing them when they%0a%3c      are needed again. It merely takes seconds for an agent who%0a%3c      has access to the facilities to install such devices in the%0a%3c      compromoised area.%0a%3c %0a%3c (5) Assume that the eavesdropper is guarding the NLJD band of frequencies.%0a%3c %0a%3c This one is a bit esoteric to the laymen, but the term NLJD refers to%0a%3c a device which is used by countermeasures technician to locate%0a%3c clandestine listening devices which may be buried under concealment%0a%3c inside of a wall, desk, drawer, behind books, buried covertly inside%0a%3c a piece of wood or other structural material which could not be inspected%0a%3c by any other means.%0a%3c %0a%3c The NLJD works much like a metal detector, only the principle involved is%0a%3c ALOT more sophisticated. The device doesnt merely search for metal.%0a%3c Rather, it searches for semiconductor junctions such as transistors and%0a%3c diodes which would be present in all "bugs" (transmitters) as well as%0a%3c in most microphones, etc..  The NLJD is mainly usefull for finding a%0a%3c clandestine device which is NOT ACTIVATED!   This has to do with one of%0a%3c the rules above (Rule #4). The eavesdropper may have the ability to%0a%3c turn the device off remotely or even manually and as such would not%0a%3c be detected with normal RF "sweeping" gear which looks for an RF/IR signal.%0a%3c (since if the device is OFF, it thusly generates no RF/IR signal).%0a%3c %0a%3c The NLJD works by transmittng a microwave frequency signal (between%0a%3c 800 - 950MHz  [depending on the version, and the laws of the country%0a%3c which the unit is sold in]. The signal power of these units is%0a%3c relatively low 20mW - 300mW for non-government ("consumer"/industry)%0a%3c versions [legal U.S.A versions a.k.a FCC approved]  and  300mW to approx%0a%3c 3 Watts for law enforcement and government units. The greater output power%0a%3c of the government models allows a higher degree of penetration into deeply%0a%3c embedded or dense materials. The typical radiated ouput for a U.S.A. version%0a%3c NLJD is 915MHz and for European versions is often 888.5MHz.%0a%3c %0a%3c Since the unit emits a microwave it thusly radiates through the airwaves%0a%3c and the eavesdropper can thusly detect it using his scanner. A clever%0a%3c eavesdropper will continuously scan the band of frequencies, or a specific%0a%3c frequency if the eavesdropper is relatively sure of the frequency on which%0a%3c the targets NLJD uses. Once the eavesdropper detects the signal, he can then%0a%3c remotely deactivate his clandestine devices.%0a%3c %0a%3c It should be noted of course, that a clever eavesdropper has at their%0a%3c disposal, a number of uniquely different methods in which to "fool" an%0a%3c NLJD unit into not detecting the listening device completely, or methods to%0a%3c fool the user of the NLJD into believing that the reflected signal is a%0a%3c false alarm.. One example is to modify the casing of the listening device,%0a%3c and RF filter all the leads when done in such a manner that they clandestine%0a%3c device will reflection a large portion of 3rd harmonics while keeping%0a%3c secondary harmonics to a minimum thus indicating to the NLJD user perhaps%0a%3c that the unit is picking up disimilar metals (sheetrock screws, nails, rebar,%0a%3c etc..) rather than semiconductors.%0a%3c I shall not detail these particular processes as its irrelevant and unwise%0a%3c but if anyone actually cares to know the methods are I can discuss that with%0a%3c you in more detail if you ask.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (6) Assume that the eavesdropper is watching for sweep receiver radiation.%0a%3c %0a%3c This is a bit more esoteric and its something which I dont feel is%0a%3c any great threat. But their might be some government experts in the%0a%3c field who are a bit more sophisticated who would say otherwise. But%0a%3c in a real life situation I dont see it happening unless the%0a%3c eavesdropper is himself a former government employee.%0a%3c %0a%3c ALL electronic equipment generates EMI (Electromagnetic Interference)%0a%3c which is essentially spurious radiation emmited unintentionally. As such%0a%3c these radio wave emmisions are also generated from any type of "sweep"%0a%3c equipment which the countermeasures technician may use.%0a%3c A sophisticated eavesdropper can detect these spurious emmisions and%0a%3c take it as a sign that sweep equipment is being used and the sweep is%0a%3c now in progress. The eavesdropper then shuts his clandestine devices%0a%3c off remotely.%0a%3c %0a%3c In reality the ability to do this is actually quite simple. Its just%0a%3c that I find it unrealistic and I dont think many buggist in this country%0a%3c go to all that trouble. Not unless its a super sophisticated operation,%0a%3c or unless the eavesdropper is being payed well to take such precautions.%0a%3c But then super sophisticated operations are not the norm. Not even close.%0a%3c Usually the bugging is done by amateurs using crude bugging equipment%0a%3c which is easily detected, and is not even concealed well on top of it.%0a%3c Most bugging devices are usually not even remotely activated and likewise%0a%3c their usually not protected against NLJD sweeps either, unless the person%0a%3c who is doing the eavesdropping is a pro which is rarely the case.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c MOSCOW RULES FOR TELEPHONE SYSTEM INSPECTIONS%0a%3c =============================================%0a%3c %0a%3c (1) Assume that the eavesdropper is listening to room sounds through%0a%3c     the telephone instrument until tests prove otherwise.%0a%3c %0a%3c (2) Assume that the eavesdropper is listening across the%0a%3c     line when the line is active.%0a%3c %0a%3c (3) Assume that the eavesdropper may be monitoring the%0a%3c     line when it is inactive.%0a%3c %0a%3c (4) Assume that the eavesdropper is monitoring the line%0a%3c     to detect TDR and RF tracing signals.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c MOSCOW RULES FOR TELEPHONE SYSTEM INSPECTIONS:%0a%3c %0a%3c (1) The eavesdropper has a variety of techniques at his disposal which%0a%3c     enable him to listen to 'room sounds' ("room audio" [note 1]) from a%0a%3c     remote location. I will not discuss that in detail, because all%0a%3c     the techniques involved in telephone and wireline attacks could fill%0a%3c     an entire book in itself.%0a%3c     Generally however, their are two main techniques that could be%0a%3c     employed. [Their are actually another 3 or 4 techniques but%0a%3c     I shant get into discussing those for the sake of brevity.]%0a%3c %0a%3c   [a] 'Hot-miked telephone' otherwise called a 'Hot-On-Hook telephone'%0a%3c       is one method, which involves modifying an actual telephone which%0a%3c       is in a targets location (in reality, the targets phone itself is%0a%3c       not modified, but an identical replacement is brought in and switched%0a%3c       with the original [this technique of switching phones of course%0a%3c       warrants caution as the target could possibly notice the difference%0a%3c       between the two by noting scuff marks, etc.. that were on the%0a%3c       original phone]. The modification consists of a circuit that will%0a%3c       allow the eavesdropper to listen to room sounds while the phone%0a%3c       is still "on-hook". The modification "drops-out" once the phone%0a%3c       is picked up for use and is brought "off-hook" (in which case,%0a%3c       the eavesdropper would then have a seperate circuit which could%0a%3c       monitor the phone conversation.%0a%3c %0a%3c   [b] The second most common method is called an "infinity transmitter",%0a%3c       which in the 'olden days' circa 1960/70 was called a "harmonica bug".%0a%3c       This is a slight variation of the hot-miked telephone. It is%0a%3c       similar in that it allows a person to listen to room audio from%0a%3c       a remote location, however the system employed need not be part of%0a%3c       the actual telephone. The device could be hidden anywhere along the%0a%3c       phone line in close proximity to the target where a seperate%0a%3c       microphone can listen to room audio which is then sent through the%0a%3c       phone lines while the phone is 'on-hook'. When the phone is lifted%0a%3c       'off-hook', the device drops-out. The device is activated remotely%0a%3c       by the eavesdropper by simply calling the targets phone line and%0a%3c       then activating the device.%0a%3c %0a%3c       Room sounds could also be monitored by simply placing a microphone%0a%3c       across any line pair, preferably a line pair which is not currently%0a%3c       activated for phone useage (ie: the second yellow-black pair.)%0a%3c       This would allow constant monitoring of the room audio even when the%0a%3c       target uses the phone (which would be on line pair 1 (red-green)%0a%3c       and thusly would not conflict. The microphone could either generate%0a%3c       its own signal 9which has the disadvantage of being easier to detect%0a%3c       because the microphone transmits constantly , or could use a microphone%0a%3c       element which requires an external voltage such as in a carbon mic.%0a%3c       In the case of carbon microphones, the eavesdropper need only apply%0a%3c       a small voltage to the line and the microphone will activate sending%0a%3c       intercepted audio down the line. The device has the advantage that it%0a%3c       is slightly harder to detect (especially inadvertently) because the unit%0a%3c       only operates when the eavesdropper has the device activated.%0a%3c       Countermeasures technicians can find the device (in its simplest form)%0a%3c       easy enough by just applying voltage to the line. But more sophisticated%0a%3c       set-ups would utilize a 4-layer diode, SCR, or a reverse polarity%0a%3c       configuration or some other method to hinder and thwart detection.%0a%3c %0a%3c (2) Rule 2 is fairly obvious and needs little explanation. Always assume%0a%3c     that a phone line can be, or currently is being monitored.%0a%3c %0a%3c     It is very important for the laymen to make the distinction between%0a%3c     the two facts in the above statement which are:%0a%3c %0a%3c          [a] the phone/line "could" be tapped.%0a%3c          [b] the phone/line "is being" tapped.%0a%3c %0a%3c     It does not make one paranoid to come to the conclusion and realization%0a%3c     that a phone "could" be tapped. It merely makes one alert and an%0a%3c     informed individual.  That does not mean that one should insist%0a%3c     that a line "is" tapped, but it should simply be considered a possibilty%0a%3c     which one must take into consideration and act accordingly on.%0a%3c %0a%3c     Thusly, if one conducts confidential business in which it would be%0a%3c     of important consequence to keep the conversation from prying ears%0a%3c     of the eavesdropper, one should always employ end-to-end encryption%0a%3c     through the use of telephone/fascimile "scramblers". [note 2]%0a%3c %0a%3c     One must make the decision for themselves regarding what is to%0a%3c     be kept secret and what can be disclosed, and you must come to%0a%3c     some sort of plan of action regarding what the different levels%0a%3c     of confidentiality are. Some secrets are worth keeping more than%0a%3c     others. In fact one might even say some secrets are so great that%0a%3c     you should not disclose them to anyone ever. That would be the%0a%3c     ultimate form of security.. As an example, if you had just%0a%3c     murdered someone, obviously any sane individual should not announce%0a%3c     that over the phone lines, no matter how secure you feel that phone%0a%3c     line is. Because their is no degree of security which is worth%0a%3c     25 years in prison or death. Even encryption (phone scramblers)%0a%3c     should not be considered secure in such cases as they can be%0a%3c     compromised rather easily by simply bypassing the encryption%0a%3c     altogether through modification by the eavesdropper, or by simply%0a%3c     liberating the code keys from the unit (which is a simple task with%0a%3c     some encryption units while alot more difficult in the better units.)%0a%3c %0a%3c Whenever a line pair is to be examined or traced (for maintenance%0a%3c purposes such as working on a phone or computer network in an office%0a%3c or home, or when a countermeasures search is being done, it is preferable%0a%3c that "audio" signals of a strange nature (line tracing signals) should%0a%3c NOT be placed across the line as they would be suspicious to an eavesdropper%0a%3c in which case the eavesdropper might deactivate remotely any devices%0a%3c which he may have installed which could put the devices in a low-profile%0a%3c status making them more difficult to detect.%0a%3c %0a%3c So how then does one trace a line without using an "audible line tracer"%0a%3c as is the standard method among technicians?  The alternative is to%0a%3c use either an RF (Radio Frequency) tracer system which is relatively%0a%3c inexpensive (and also has many advatages over audible tracers such as%0a%3c the ability to track wires through walls without having to open up the wall%0a%3c or structure for physical examination) or one could utilize an "ultrasonic"%0a%3c tracer device which sends an inaudible signal down the line. These%0a%3c aultrasonic tracers are an indespensible tool which come in two forms.%0a%3c The first is simply a aultrasonic tone tracer and merely produces a%0a%3c single tone for identifying line pairs. The second type of ultrasonic%0a%3c device actually modulates a voice signals onto a wire pair so that it%0a%3c is inaudible and above both the range of human hearing and likewise%0a%3c cannot be picked up by either microphones of any type and cannot be%0a%3c demodulated by any type of standard amplifier unit which is not designed%0a%3c to amplify sounds above the standard human hearing/speaking range.%0a%3c Only a specialized matching ultrasonic demodulation amplifier can%0a%3c intercept and convert the signals back into the human hearing range.%0a%3c %0a%3c Keep in mind with the above however, that rule #3 below shall apply.%0a%3c Rule #3 states that the eavesdropper "may" be able to hear your line%0a%3c tracing with the phone on-hook.  So one has to balance this%0a%3c consideration out. Nine times out of Ten you would be better off sending%0a%3c these signals down the line because most eavesdroppers DO NOT monitor%0a%3c a phone which is on-hook, nor do they look for signals on inactive lines%0a%3c (not unless they are professionals, or are simply getting payed alot%0a%3c of money to do that extra work which is often unnecessary).%0a%3c But if your up against a sophisticated eavesdropper and you know of%0a%3c his capabilities it would probably be wise in such case NOT to send any%0a%3c strange signals down a wire pair other than ordinary phone conversations.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (3) Most of the time, telephone surveillance, whether it be the%0a%3c     interception of phone conversations where the phone is off-hook,%0a%3c     or even monitoring of room conversations when the line is on-hook%0a%3c     involves the use of some sort of "activation" device which records%0a%3c     the conversations when and only when those conversations are present.%0a%3c     When the conversation ceases the device will shut itself off (usually)%0a%3c     so as to conserve tape (and in addition make it easier for the%0a%3c     eavesdropper to find the conversations in the recorded tapes.%0a%3c %0a%3c     When dealing with recording telephone calls, a device is used which%0a%3c     monitors the voltage on the line for off-hook/on-hook conditions%0a%3c     and then activates a special tape recorder (with a remote activation%0a%3c     jack) when the phone goes off-hook. [although a more clever eavesdropper%0a%3c     would not use such a device but would rather use a VOX (voice%0a%3c     [sound level] activated unit as opposed a voltage sensing unit which%0a%3c     can actually be "tricked" as well as "detected" alot more easily%0a%3c     which should be coupled to an inductive pick-up coil (or at the least%0a%3c     a high-impedance capacitively coupled interface). VOX units too also%0a%3c     have their problems, namely they can have havoc wreaked upon them%0a%3c     by the use of masking devices or "telephone security units" which are%0a%3c     now widely sold on the market for a couple hundred dollars. These%0a%3c     telephone security units have the ability to defeat most simple%0a%3c     eavesdropping methods utilizing  techniques such as masking as well%0a%3c     as "Line Balancing". The latter technique of balancing performed by%0a%3c     raising the voltage, while the current is simultaneously lowered.%0a%3c     Such a technique does not interfere with the PSTN Central Office and%0a%3c     will give the user a dial-tone when the line is raised off-hook(600 Ohms)%0a%3c     and will thusly defeats most voltage activated devices such as simple%0a%3c     telephone tap transmistters as well as drop-out relays (telephone%0a%3c     recorder controllers).%0a%3c %0a%3c     The foolish individual could conclude that if most eavesdroppers%0a%3c     used a voltage activated device that only recorded audio when the%0a%3c     phone was "off-hook", then the line should be secured in an "on-hook"%0a%3c     condition. Example, a person could then transmit his voice within%0a%3c     the household or office while the phone was still "on-hook" using a%0a%3c     relatively simple circuit to do that and "supposedly" that would%0a%3c     alow for safe conversation, and it would be safe "if" a voltage%0a%3c     activated telephone recording adapter was used.%0a%3c     However, many eavesdroppers (sophisticated ones) may be a bit more%0a%3c     clever than that. The clever eavesdropper may monitor a line pair%0a%3c     even when it is inactive (such as when a phone is "on-hook".)%0a%3c     This would allow the eavesdropper to hear  "AUDIO" [note 1]%0a%3c     even when the phone is off-hook.  Note I use the word AUDIO very%0a%3c     carefully. Because in such an instance, the eavsdropper may NOT%0a%3c     just be listening to secret conversations which occur "on-hook"%0a%3c     but he may be listening to other audio which could be a potential%0a%3c     threat to the eavesdropper such a the sounds of audible line tracing,%0a%3c     ultrasonic line tracing or ultrasonic voice modulation, as well%0a%3c     as RF tracing, and lastly the eavesdropper could be looking for%0a%3c     the signals emmenating from a TDR (see rule #4 explanation).%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (4) The last rule is a rather esoterical one which is of more concern%0a%3c     to the countermeasures technician who is performing the search%0a%3c     as opposed to concern of your ordinary individual or businessman%0a%3c     concerned with the rules to insuring privacy.%0a%3c %0a%3c     Rule #4 is just a follow up to rule #3 which states that an eavesdropper%0a%3c     could possibly be monitoring the inactive line pair. In rule #4 we%0a%3c     get specific in saying that an eavesdropper may be looking for%0a%3c     RF signals or TDR signals which may be an indication of a countermeasures%0a%3c     "sweep" which is being conducted. This should concern the eavesdropper%0a%3c     for obvious reasons, which are that he could possibly be discovered%0a%3c     very soon if the technician is a competant one, or if the eavesdroppers%0a%3c     set-up is crude or poorly installed in which case it could possibly%0a%3c     be detected.%0a%3c %0a%3c     I have already explained ultrasonic and RF tracing above in rule 3,%0a%3c     so I'll just deal with TDR's.%0a%3c %0a%3c     A TDR is common abbreviation for a device known as a Time Domain%0a%3c     Reflectometer. You pronounce the units name by simply saying the%0a%3c     letters..   "T" - "D" - "R".%0a%3c %0a%3c     The TDR is a common tool of anyone who works exensively with wires%0a%3c     (or fiber optic cabling) of any type. The type of TDR we are discussing%0a%3c     is only for the "wire" and not "fiber optic" type.%0a%3c     TDR's are used by cable company technicians, computer network%0a%3c     technicians, telephone lineman or repair personell, as well as%0a%3c     surveillance countermeasures technicians.%0a%3c %0a%3c     A TDR is a device (usually a hand-held size device although slightly%0a%3c     larger and more powerfull bench-top units are available) which emits%0a%3c     a mild powered signal into a wire pair. This signal gets sent down%0a%3c     a wire pair, or through a coaxial cable and gets partially reflected%0a%3c     off of any discontinuity on the line pair. Herein, I'll refer to any%0a%3c     discontinuous reflections as an "anomaly" on the wire. I use the word%0a%3c     as opposed to discontinuity (because its easier to type) and because%0a%3c     much like an anomoly it is indicative of the unknown. And thats what%0a%3c     your looking for when doing a TSCM TDR sweep of a wire pair.%0a%3c     Your looking for unknown or strange situations.%0a%3c     It is these anomalies which the technician is looking for which are a%0a%3c     possible source of the problem (or could even indicate that everything%0a%3c     is normal if their is supposed to be an anomoly at some point).%0a%3c %0a%3c     The word "anomaly" is a generic term which refers to anything on the%0a%3c     line which will interfere with the signal going through the line.%0a%3c     To put it another way, it is something which causes part of the signal to%0a%3c     literally reflect backwards from the point of origin instead of traveling%0a%3c     freely and smoothly through the wire.%0a%3c %0a%3c     This "reflection" of the signal is what the TDR is looking to receive%0a%3c     after it emits the original pulse. The reflection which could be of%0a%3c     varying degrees of intensity depending on how large the anomaly is.%0a%3c     The larger the anomaly, the larger the reflection, and occasionaly that%0a%3c     means the bigger the problem. Ideally the signal is supposed to travel%0a%3c     through the wire impeded as little as possible.  Anomalies are caused%0a%3c     by a wide variety of things too great to discuss here. They can be%0a%3c     caused by imperfections in the wire itself, they can be caused by%0a%3c     splices in the line, they can be caused by "connectors" on a wireline%0a%3c     which join 2 wires together or a wire to a piece of equipment. Anomalies%0a%3c     can be caused by "termination plugs" which are a dummy loads placed%0a%3c     at the end of a unused wirepair. Anomalies can also be caused by%0a%3c     physical hardware on the line such as splitters, filters, junction boxes,%0a%3c     66/110blocks, entrance bridges, and the list can go on and on.%0a%3c %0a%3c     The countermeasures technician is primarily interested in looking for%0a%3c     things such as splices on the line which could be indicative of a%0a%3c     telephone tap.  Keep in mind, that the word "splice" does not necessarily%0a%3c     preclude that a line was physically "spliced" (ie: cut and then%0a%3c     re-connected.) It also can imply a simple "tap" on the line where one%0a%3c     wire (alligator clip, etc..) is touching upon the original wireline.%0a%3c     TDR's have a typical range of 1,000 - 10,000 feet. A typical handheld%0a%3c     TDR used by computer network installers will have ranges of 1,000 - 2k%0a%3c     feet. Countermeasures technicians often utilize slightly more powerfull%0a%3c     models extending 2,000 - 5,000 feet so they can have the ability to%0a%3c     trace large amounts of wires present in office buildings. And benchmodel%0a%3c     units which are usually the most powerfull (although some handheld%0a%3c     units are capable of such) can extend upwards of 10,000 or more feet.%0a%3c     These units can pinpoint  "flaws" or "anomalies" on a wireline to%0a%3c     a resolution of millimeters which makes them damned accurate devices%0a%3c     which can tell you exactly where the flaw is down the line. (typically%0a%3c     however in high powered devices the resolution is limited to feet or%0a%3c     meters).%0a%3c %0a%3c     The TDR is most effective when it is used on a routine basis and a%0a%3c     day-to-day (or more likely week-to-week or moth-to-month) comparison%0a%3c     can be made between the different or same results.  Ideally, the%0a%3c     results of the TDR should always be the same.  Should a result be%0a%3c     significantly different on one occasion, or something appears to have%0a%3c     been spliced/tapped onto the line it will be readily apparent.%0a%3c %0a%3c     Of course for the TDR test to be most effective, it should be realized%0a%3c     that the initial tests of the TDR must be done when the line was "clean".%0a%3c     If the line was tapped in the first place the first time you tested%0a%3c     it, then all subsequent comparisons thereafter are of little use because%0a%3c     you cant compare a "clean" like with a "tapped" line.%0a%3c %0a%3c     However, that factor doesnt render a TDR test completely useless.%0a%3c     One does not necessarily rely solely on the technique of comparison%0a%3c     from one time to another.  Other methods exist for using the TDR%0a%3c     which are a combination of tracing the line physically with the TDR%0a%3c     from the demarc point inwards to the telephone instruments and%0a%3c     physically searching the line for taps/splices in conjunction with%0a%3c     the use of voltmeters or telephone analyzers to search for%0a%3c     imbalanced loops, or imbalanced lines to ground, crossed line pairs%0a%3c     as well as suspicious line impedances.%0a%3c     Likewise, the search should occur from the demarc point outwards%0a%3c     towards the telephone company as far as one can go. The search should%0a%3c     extend out the end of the customers property,  but a countermeasures%0a%3c     technician who does not mind breaking a few laws might feel free%0a%3c     to extend the test point up to the neighborhood cross connect cabinets%0a%3c     where the distribution cable meets the feeders.%0a%3c %0a%3c                             [note 1]%0a%3c %0a%3c   In surveillance lingo, the word "AUDIO" is often used as opposed to%0a%3c   the word "SOUND" or "CONVERSATION". The meanings are almost synonymous,%0a%3c   but their is a slight difference.  The word "audio" is used because%0a%3c   it denotes any type of intelligence which could be collected and is%0a%3c   not limited to intercepting spoken conversations (spoken words). %0a%3c %0a%3c                             [note 2]%0a%3c %0a%3c   Even encryption (phone scramblers) should not be considered secure%0a%3c   as they can be compromised rather easily by simply bypassing the%0a%3c   encryption altogether through modification of the telephone instrument%0a%3c   by the eavesdropper, or by simply liberating the code keys from the unit.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c -----------------------------%0a%3c WHAT THIS MEANS TO YOU AND ME%0a%3c -----------------------------%0a%3c One may ponder the question of  "what the hell does this article have%0a%3c to do at all with me?"%0a%3c How does this concern you if you dont run a company?%0a%3c How does this concern you if you are not doing anything illegal?%0a%3c How does this conern you if you believe your not a target being watched?%0a%3c %0a%3c I have no answer. Take from this article what you will. It is provided%0a%3c for informational purposes. I have discussed not only quite a bit about%0a%3c surveillance as well as countermeasures, but also the some of the terms%0a%3c which is used by people who work in that field. These are terms which you%0a%3c may run across one day if you work in the field of general security, and%0a%3c you will thusly be able to speak a bit more authoritatively to your%0a%3c colleagues who may not know much about espionage.%0a%3c %0a%3c But if you have any respect for your own privacy, then you should heed%0a%3c some of the advice discussed herein.%0a%3c %0a%3c You need not be a corporate executive to realize the need not only for your%0a%3c privacy but the need to recognize how many people by their own acts%0a%3c contribute to the privacy violations. They do this by using cordless phones,%0a%3c cellular phones, by using paging beepers and even by holding confidential%0a%3c conversations on unsecured phone lines instead of in person.%0a%3c %0a%3c I write this specific article for those people on computer bulletin board%0a%3c systems, and this is aimed SPECIFICALLY at those who refer to themselves as%0a%3c "computer hackers"   or  "telephone phreaks".. If you do not recognize the%0a%3c value in this article then you are a great fool indeed.%0a%3c %0a%3c Remember folks.. Paranoia is our friend. You never know who is watching%0a%3c or listening.   Always assume the worst and thusly disclose the least%0a%3c you can; even to so-called friends.%0a%3c                    ----------------------------------%0a%3c Never discuss anything illegal over a telephone be it landline or cordless.%0a%3c %0a%3c Never keep any incriminating material at your home. Or at the very least%0a%3c any such information if illegal, should not be 'feloniously' illegal.%0a%3c %0a%3c Never discuss any majorly illegal acts (in my book thats defined as anything%0a%3c thats a felony) with anyone else, even friends. And if you do, then you%0a%3c should be sufficiently vague and even intentionally misleading to your%0a%3c friends so as to give the eavesdroppers "misiformation".%0a%3c %0a%3c Never disclose to any friend the full capabilities of your power, your%0a%3c knowledge, etc.. If necessary intentionally mislead those friends by%0a%3c overstating or understating your capabilities or knowledge in order to%0a%3c feed misinformation to an eavesdropper. This can be done to "spook" your%0a%3c eavesdropper and make them enact a move prematurely, or to make them%0a%3c believe what you want them to believe for whatever reason you see fit.%0a%3c In addition, feed just enough thruthfull information so as to 'whet the%0a%3c appetite' of the eavesdropper and not give away your conversation as%0a%3c total obvious misinformation.%0a
